es. The dance-song elements of the medieval carole were so strongly woven into the vernacular cultural fabric of the British Isles that their threads can be traced through the folk songs and dances of subsequent centuries. This study contextualizes the written evidence and re-integrates the various components of the activity in order to illuminate our understanding of the universally popular medieval, participatory, pastime of carolling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCarols, medieval performance arts, medieval song, dance history, music history, folk music,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781802700589?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781802700589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781802700589/original  a978-3-11-076700-1  DG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2b2022  a978-3-11-076709-4  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK